Scatter Plot (sns.scatterplot)
- Use: Displays the relationship between two continuous variables.
- Example: Plotting sepal length vs. sepal width in the Iris dataset helps identify clusters or correlations.
- Insight: Useful for detecting trends, clusters, and outliers in data.

ðŸ“ˆ 2. Line Plot (sns.lineplot)
- Use: Shows trends over time or ordered categories.
- Example: Visualizing monthly sales data to see growth or decline.
- Insight: Ideal for time-series analysis and understanding progression of values.

ðŸ“‰ 3. Histogram / Distribution Plot (sns.histplot / sns.displot)
- Use: Represents the distribution of a single variable.
- Example: Plotting the distribution of customer ages in a dataset.
- Insight: Helps identify skewness, spread, and whether data follows a normal distribution.

ðŸŸ¦ 4. Box Plot (sns.boxplot)
- Use: Summarizes data distribution using quartiles and highlights outliers.
- Example: Comparing salary distributions across different departments.
- Insight: Great for spotting variability, median values, and extreme outliers.
Q1. Load the "titanic" dataset using the load_dataset function of seaborn. Use Plotly express to plot a
scatter plot for age and fare columns in the titanic dataset.
import plotly.graph_objects as go
import seaborn as sns
titanic = sns.load_dataset('titanic')
print(titanic.head())
fig = go.Figure()
fig.add_trace(go.Scatter(x=titanic.age,y=titanic.fare,mode='markers'))
fig.show()

Q2. Using the tips dataset in the Plotly library, plot a box plot using Plotly express.
import plotly.graph_objects as go
import seaborn as sns
tips = sns.load_dataset("tips")
fig = go.Figure()
fig.add_trace(go.Box(
    x=tips["day"],          # categorical variable
    y=tips["total_bill"],   # numeric variable
    name="Total Bill"
))
fig.show()


Q3. Using the tips dataset in the Plotly library, Plot a histogram for x= "sex" and y="total_bill" column in the tips dataset. Also, use the "smoker" column with the pattern_shape parameter and the "day"
column with the color parameter.
import plotly.express as px

# Load tips dataset
df = px.data.tips()

# Create histogram
fig = px.histogram(
    df,
    x="sex",             # categorical variable
    y="total_bill",      # numeric variable
    color="day",         # color by day
    pattern_shape="smoker",  # pattern by smoker status
    barmode="group",     # group bars side by side
    title="Histogram of Total Bill by Sex, Day, and Smoker Status"
)

fig.show()


Q4. Using the iris dataset in the Plotly library, Plot a scatter matrix plot, using the "species" column for
the color parameter.
Note: Use "sepal_length", "sepal_width", "petal_length", "petal_width" columns only with the
dimensions parameter.
import plotly.graph_objects as go
import seaborn as sns
iris = sns.load_dataset("iris")
fig = go.Figure


import plotly.express as px

df = px.data.iris()

fig = px.scatter_matrix(
    df,
    dimensions=["sepal_length", "sepal_width", "petal_length", "petal_width"],
    color="species",
    title="Scatter Matrix of Iris Dataset"
)

fig.show()

Q5. What is Distplot? Using Plotly express, plot a distplot.
Ans. A distplot (short for distribution plot) is a visualization that shows the distribution of a dataset.
- It combines a histogram (frequency of values) with a density curve (smooth estimate of the distribution).
- In Seaborn, sns.distplot() was commonly used, but it is now deprecated.
- In Plotly Express, we achieve the same effect using px.histogram with the marginal or histnorm parameters to show distribution and density.

import plotly.express as px

# Load dataset
df = px.data.tips()

# Create distplot (distribution of total_bill)
fig = px.histogram(
    df,
    x="total_bill",          # numeric column
    nbins=30,                # number of bins
    marginal="box",          # add a box plot on the side
    histnorm="density",      # normalize histogram to show density
    title="Distribution Plot of Total Bill"
)

fig.show()




